04838nam a22007215i 9780813550978DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t20112011nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135509787 a10.36019/97808135509782doi  a(DE-B1597)529403  a(OCoLC)768732013  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aKFC1196 .P35 2011 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a345.794/02770269a345.7940277a345.794027702691 aPaik, Leslie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDiscretionary Justice :bLooking Inside a Juvenile Drug Court /cLeslie Paik. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCritical Issues in Crime and Society00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tChapter 1. Inside the Black Box of Drug Court Justice -- tChapter 2. Setting and Methods -- tChapter 3. What Court Day Is He? Intercourt Variations -- tChapter 4. Building Accountability through Assessments of Noncompliance -- tChapter 5. Social Construction of Drug Test Results -- tChapter 6. It's Not Just His Probation, It's Mine: Parental Involvement in the Drug Court -- tChapter 7. Youth Trajectories in the Court -- tChapter 8. The (In)justice of Discretion: Drug Courts as Therapeutic Punishment and Therapeutic Justice -- tAppendix A. Methods -- tAppendix B. Concepts and Terms -- tAppendix C. Additional Resources -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJuvenile drug courts are on the rise in the United States, as a result of a favorable political climate and justice officials' endorsement of the therapeutic jurisprudence movement--the concept of combining therapeutic care with correctional discipline. The goal is to divert nonviolent youth drug offenders into addiction treatment instead of long-term incarceration. Discretionary Justice overviews the system, taking readers behind the scenes of the juvenile drug court. Based on fifteen months of ethnographic fieldwork and interviews at a California court, Leslie Paik explores the staff's decision-making practices in assessing the youths' cases, concentrating on the way accountability and noncompliance are assessed. Using the concept of "workability," Paik demonstrates how compliance, and what is seen by staff as "noncompliance," are the constructed results of staff decisions, fluctuating budgets, and sometimes questionable drug test results. While these courts largely focus on holding youths responsible for their actions, this book underscores the social factors that shape how staff members view progress in the court. Paik also emphasizes the perspectives of children and parents. Given the growing emphasis on individual responsibility in other settings, such as schools and public welfare agencies, Paik's findings are relevant outside the juvenile justice system.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aDrug abusexTreatmentxLaw and legislationzCalifornia. 0aDrug courtszCalifornia. 0aJuvenile courtszCalifornia. 0aJuvenile delinquentsxRehabilitationzCalifornia. 0aYouthxDrug usezCalifornia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066331040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813550978423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813550978.jpg  a978-3-11-066331-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-068861-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  